Architecture: In day-to-day life, architecture is the design and construction of buildings. In technology, architecture refers to the design of a computer. It is the organizing of all the parts of the computer. Different computers have different architecture depending on what they are meant to handle.

Architecture is also used to describe the overall design of a computer program. This means how the various parts of the program are organized relative to each other, and also how that program is designed in terms of how it will interact with other programs in a computer.

EXAMPLE: Some computers’ architecture is set up so that the computer does the same thing over and over all day. Other computers’ architecture is set up so that people can use the computer for personal reasons.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

ASP.NET: This stands for Active Server Pages dot (.) NET.

Early in the development of the Web, web pages were static — they had only text and images, and the text and images didn’t change unless the creator of the web page edited the files that made up the web page.

Website creators needed a way to make some of the content on a web page dynamic — the exact content could change based on factors such as the specific identity of the person requesting the web page; the time or date; the specific inventory available for sale at any point in time; etc.

One such method was Active Server Pages. This was a way to combine the standard language of web pages (Hyper Text Markup Language) with specific computer code that would create web page content on the fly as needed. It was quite popular in the late 1990s and early 2000s.

A framework is a set of software, documentation, etc. that form a basic platform on which to create large software applications. ASP.NET is a framework for making complex websites.

ASP.NET is simply a set of tools offered by Microsoft, used for making websites. ASP.NET allows one to develop complicated websites that contain large amounts of information and sections. It is considered an advanced tool for those interested in making websites and web pages.

The terms "ASP.NET" uses the letters "ASP," but ASP.NET has very little to do with ASP. The creators of ASP.NET used the "ASP" acronym basically as a marketing element when they released ASP.NET.

EXAMPLE: The website MySpace was created using ASP.NET.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Assembly Language: Also called assembly code. Computers “speak” and “think” in numbers. This is called “machine language." Due to the fact that people speak in words, it is sometimes difficult for us to read and write in machine language — even though it’s what the computer would prefer. To handle this, people invented “assembly language," a simple language that replaces the numbers used in machine language with easily-remembered English words and phrases that people can understand.

An “assembler” is a program built into the computer that automatically translates the assembly language (easily understood by people) into machine language (the numbers a computer can use to perform its functions).

EXAMPLE: Instead of writing “01100110” to tell the computer to begin its work, assembly language lets you use a word like “LOAD” instead. The assembler then converts the instruction "LOAD" into "01100110" and passes that on to the computer.

Back end: The part of a website or software program that performs vital computing functions, but is not typically seen by the user of the site or program. This includes things like a database (an organized collection of information stored by the site or program).

Back end developers are those skilled in the technology required to create and organize the back end.

EXAMPLE: In a software program that allows a warehouse manager to monitor and manage the contents of the warehouse, the back end would be the collection of data about the warehouse contents. The front end would be the screens the manager uses to view and change that data.

BASIC: Stands for "Beginner's All-purpose Symbolic Instruction Code." BASIC is a computer programming language that was developed in the mid-1960s to provide a way for students to write simple computer programs. BASIC has evolved into a more advanced and powerful language that can be used to create programs for modern computers.

EXAMPLE: Many computer games from the 1970s and 1980s were created using BASIC.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

C: One of the most widely-used programming languages. C was developed between 1969 and 1973. Many other languages have borrowed concepts and technology from C. The most up to date version (called C11) was approved in December 2011. C is used in the creation of many things, from operating systems (the basic program that allows a computer to perform any tasks at all), to apps, games, and business productivity programs. It is a very wide-ranging language with many capabilities.

EXAMPLE: When you buy a new printer, you often need to put a special program on your computer that allows the computer to interact with that printer. That special program might be written in C.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

C#: C# is a programming language that was invented in 1999 by Microsoft. C# has many uses and can be used to create several types of things. The purpose of C# is to precisely lay out steps of instructions that a computer can perform to accomplish a task. Anything that a computer can physically do can be programmed using C#. C# is one of the most commonly used programming languages. It is well-suited to make large software programs that enable businesses to automate business processes.

Some uses of C# are:

-Sending or receiving information to and from a database

-Displaying a very clear picture in movies and video games

-Controlling other machines that you connect to your computer

-Playing music and sound effects on a computer

EXAMPLE: Some parts of the Windows operating system were created using C#.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

C++: C++ (pronounced “C plus plus”) is a programming language that was created in the beginning of the 1980s. It is based on one of the most popular computer programming languages: C. It can be used in conjunction with some other programming languages. C++ has many uses and can be used to create several types of things.

Many computers contain something that was created using C++ as it is one of the most common programming languages.

EXAMPLE: Many computer games were made using C++.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Subprogram: A subprogram is a set of computer instructions to be used by a main computer program. A subprogram performs a task that you may want to do over and over again at various times. The main computer program could do some of its own actions in a specific sequence, then ask the subprogram to do its tasks, and then continue on where it was before it asked the subprogram to do its tasks.

Another term for this is “subroutine,” since a routine is just a set of computer instructions — a computer program.

EXAMPLE: Within a computer program used to operate a college, there could be a subprogram that checks to see if any new students have been enrolled since you last used the program. The main program uses that subprogram as it is starting up, gets the data on any new students, and then continues on with its primary functions.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Call: “To call” means to demand or direct something. In normal English, “call” could be used in a phrase like “This calls for celebration!” In computers, a call is a direction by a main computer program to execute the tasks of a subprogram. More specifically, a “call” is when a program temporarily transfers control of the computer to a subprogram. Once the subprogram is done executing, control of the computer is returned to the main program. A program can make many “calls” to multiple subprograms as the program performs its sequence of tasks.

EXAMPLE: If you were using a video game program, the video game program could call a “high score” subprogram after every game ended to make the words “High Score” pop up on the screen.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Environment: The overall structure within which a user, computer, etc. operates. This is often used to mean “the combination of physical hardware and operating system that a computer uses.”

EXAMPLE: Your computer might have an environment that is specifically set up for creating and modifying detailed artistic drawings. This could mean that the computer’s display and the speed at which it operates are set up in order to best facilitate those tasks.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Folder: Folders are a way of organizing files on a computer. Files are collections of data stored on a computer. The data in a file is organized in a specific manner, usually based on how that data is going to be used by the computer. Files each have their own name and contain their own data. Files are often stored in a folder. Folders are usually given a descriptive name.

EXAMPLE: A holiday greeting letter you type up on a computer could be saved as a file and stored in a “Greetings” folder on your computer.

Front end: The term "front end" has to do with how websites are presented and interacted with.

The front end of a website is the part of the site that a user directly interacts with and sees, as opposed to the back end, which consists of things behind the scenes that users don’t typically deal with directly.

The front end is handled by the web browser. It encompasses things like preparing the requested website files for display, formatting the text and images that appear on the screen, handling user interaction with the web page (clicking on text and images, etc.), and sending information back to the web server (things like requests for further web pages or user information that was entered on a web page).

EXAMPLE: The text and pictures on a website are the “front end.” The back end refers to all the functions that happen on the web server for that site.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Installer: “Install” means to put something inside a computer that the computer can then use. You can install software and you can install hardware. An installer is a specialized computer program that installs other programs on a computer.

EXAMPLE: When you put a new game on your computer, you use an installer.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Interactive: “Interactive” means that two things influence and affect one another. In computers, “interactive” refers to a computer that is able to be communicated with and directed to perform activities by a human; these activities involve the person using the computer. An interactive computer is a computer that you can affect in some way (like moving a pointer on a screen and selecting something) and which will respond in some manner. Most (if not all) computers you’ve handled have been interactive.

A non-interactive computer is one that simply performs a specific, predetermined set of actions and does not respond to any user actions — for example, a computer that controls the display of an electronic billboard. The computer has no method for receiving input, and as long as it is turned on, all it does is display the same images, one after the other.

EXAMPLE: An interactive computer might be a display at a mall that allows you to enter in a type of store or item, and then shows you the name and location of any stores in the mall that match the words you entered.

JavaScript: JavaScript is a computer language that works on most computers. It is useful in making websites. JavaScript is used mainly to make websites more dynamic (websites that have content that changes based on user action or other factors, rather than being static in appearance and content). There are many other uses for JavaScript; it is used in the creation of many different types of computer programs.

EXAMPLE: JavaScript can be used to make videos that start to play as soon as a user moves their mouse over the video.

JQuery: JQuery (pronounced “Jay-Query”) is a library of pre-made JavaScript instructions that help computer programmers create websites. A library is a collection of files. A library can also be a set of automatic commands that a computer performs. Programmers often make libraries of useful computer code so that others don't have to do all that work again — they can simply find the code in the library.

EXAMPLE: JQuery can be used to quickly add a feature to a website, such as a feature that displays a set of pictures, one after another, on the screen.

Load: There are two common meanings for this term in the computer industry:

1. To transfer memory from one location to another (usually the original memory is kept intact).

EXAMPLE: When you load a file, it usually means that you are opening a file from memory and viewing it on your screen.

2. The amount of demand on a computer program or computer system.

EXAMPLE: One of the computers in a computer network holds information that 100 other networked computers need to access — these 100 other computers are the consumers of that data. If at any one point in time, 80 of the 100 computers are trying to access the computer that has the information, you would say that the load on the "data computer" is 80%.

Load testing: You can run tests on a program or website where you simulate it being used by many individual users at once in order to see how it performs under those conditions. This is called “load testing.”

EXAMPLE: There are many companies that offer load testing as a service.

Object: You are surrounded by objects — your furniture, your TV, etc. Objects have a state and a behavior. The state of an object is the size, color, etc. The behavior of an object is what the object does — the actions it takes.

EXAMPLE: A race car is an example of an object. Things that describe its state are: engine type, engine horsepower, wheel size, gas tank capacity, etc. Things that describe its behavior are: accelerate, decelerate, turn right, turn left, etc. In computers, objects are parts of computer programs. They share a similarity with real life objects: they have a state and a behavior.

Another example: An application might work with a “Customer” object. Again, the state of an object is the characteristics and attributes of the object, and the behavior is what the object does. In our example, the “Customer” object could have states like ‘active’ or ‘deleted.’ It could have behavior like ‘Upgrade Rewards Level’ or ‘Add to Family Account.’ Objects are one of the first things you think about when designing a program. An object is something on a computer that you can click on, interact with, move around, etc. It can also be something behind the scenes that is made up of information and procedures to manipulate information. An object is what actually runs in the computer.

Another example: Let’s say you wanted to make two different types of cars on a computer. Each car would be an object. Each object (car) would have its own size, shape, color, speed, distance it can travel without needing more gas, etc.

  1.  <Pages 742-744: Tabs>

Object-oriented programming (OOP): There are different approaches you can take to programming. Object-oriented programming is an approach to programming that focuses on objects and information (as opposed an approach that focuses on actions, or some other approach). The first step in OOP is determining what objects you are going to be dealing with and how all the objects relate to each other. OOP is a popular approach to programming computers that is used in many languages.

EXAMPLE: If you were creating a website using object-oriented programming, you would focus on all the things you wanted included in the website (pictures, pages, videos, etc.) first, then design the basic outline of each type of thing from there, always focusing on the information and objects to be used by and contained in the website.

JSON: Stands for JavaScript Object Notation. JSON is code used in exchanging information. The format is relatively easy for humans to read and write, while also being understood and handled by computers. JSON is mainly used to transmit data back and forth between a server and an Internet application. JSON is compatible with many languages.

EXAMPLE: If you designed a website, you could use JSON to ensure your app smoothly exchanges information with the computers of people visiting that website.

Key: In computers, a key can be a few different things, including:

1. One of the buttons you press with your fingers on the keyboard.

EXAMPLE: One of the uses of the “shift” key is to capitalize letters.

2. When dealing with the storage of computer information, a key is a unique identifier for a piece or collection of information.

EXAMPLE: If you were storing records for student performances in a computer program used to operate a school, and each record was for a specific student, you would have a unique piece of information in each record that could be used to exactly identify that record. This could be a student ID number, the student's Social Security Number, etc. The important thing would be that the key would never be used to identify any other student, as that could lead to confusion.

3. Another word for a password.

EXAMPLE: The network “key” is the password used to access the network.

Let: "Let" is a command you type into a computer that tells it to do something. The “Let” command tells your computer to let something occur.

EXAMPLE: You could type "Let: Computer restart" to get your computer to turn off, then back on.

Machine Cycle: A computer can only do one thing at a time. Each action must be broken down into a series of the most basic instructions. To complete an instruction, a computer does a series of steps called a machine cycle.

The machine cycle is often called the "fetch-decode-execute" cycle because it is composed of:

  • Fetch: Get the next instruction to be executed
  • Decode: Translate the instruction from a coded form into a form the computer can understand
  • Execute: Performing the instruction

One of the primary performance ratings of a computer is how many machine cycles it can perform per second.

EXAMPLE: Most actions you do with a computer require hundreds or thousands of machine cycles per action. Most computers are able to perform billions of machine cycles per second.

Reader: In computers, reading is when the computer acquires information from a storage and is able to perform with that information. A reader is something that obtains and looks at stored information from another thing.

EXAMPLE: A CD reader would be the part of a computer that reads CDs.

Scripting: Scripting is creating a series of commands that cause your computer to automatically perform actions. Tasks can be very valuable to automate because, with automation, instructions don't have to be entered in again every time you want to perform those tasks. Scripting languages have some of the following characteristics:

  • The code is written in a similar way to English, meaning it is easier for people to understand and read than some more highly technical languages.

  • You can use it in conjunction with HTML so that you can add features to websites.

  • You use scripting language to program automatic functions into a computer that are performed without computer’s user having to type out every instruction.

The term is similar in meaning to a movie script, which tells actors what to do. A scripting language controlled the operation of a normally-interactive program, giving it a sequence of work to do all in one batch. For instance, one could put a series of editing commands in a file, and tell an editor to run that "script" as if those commands had been typed interactively.

Velocity: This is how much work people are assigned to handle in one set period of time. This can be determined by looking over how fast they took on their last assignment or by simply asking them how much they think they can get done in a set period of time. Velocity is how fast a project will be completed and its completion date can be determined thereby.

EXAMPLE: Five people are creating a new computer game. You meet with them every two weeks to check their progress. They tell you they can finish one level a week. Because you meet with them every two weeks, the determined velocity is that they will complete two levels.

Web application: A web application is a computer program that uses both the browser and the web server to accomplish its functions.

Note that this differs from the way many computer programs work, where the entire program resides on your computer.

The browser handles the display of information to the user and gives the user a place to enter instructions for the program. The web server handles various data processing actions based on the user instructions.

EXAMPLE: Dropbox is a popular web application.

Perl: A popular computer programming language developed by Larry Wall in the 1980s.

EXAMPLE: Perl has been referred to as the “Swiss Army Knife of programming languages” because of its flexibility.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Volatile: “Volatile” is used to describe something that can change. In computers, we use “volatile” when talking about a certain type of information stored in a computer. It simply means that when the power is turned off, the information is no longer there. Information that is stored in a computer that doesn't erase when you turn off the computer is not volatile.

EXAMPLE: You have an alarm clock plugged into the wall and set the time. Someone unplugs the alarm clock. You plug it back in and now the time displays “12:00”. The time on an alarm clock is volatile.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

High-level language: A computer programming language that is designed to be easy for people to read and write. High-level languages look somewhat like English, and the words used have similar meanings to what they mean in English.

EXAMPLE: Code written as follows would be high level language:

Print “hello”;

The code tells the computer to write out the word "hello" on the screen.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

Low-level Language: A programming language that is designed to be efficient for a computer to execute. This is called a low-level language because it is brought close down to the computer’s level of physical construction. A person attempting to read a low level language may become confused because the lower the language, the less it is like English.

Most people find low-level languages more difficult to learn than high-level languages.

EXAMPLE: Computer instructions in a low-level language can look like this: MOV AL, 61h

This code tells the computer to store a number in a specific location in the computer's memory.

An instruction in a high-level language, however, might look like this:

age = 18;

Assembly language and machine language are low-level languages.

Interpreter: An interpreter is a special program that converts high-level language (similar to English) instructions into low-level language (designed to be easy for a computer to execute) instructions. An interpreter converts code one instruction at a time, rather than converting the entire set of instructions in the program prior to execution.

In other words, the interpreter will read an instruction, convert it to language the computer can understand, have the computer execute that instruction, then go on to the next instruction in the program and repeat.

EXAMPLE: Interpreted computer languages use interpreters.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>


COMPILERS AND INTERPRETERS

Computer programmers write programs in a language they can read. They also use a certain specialized program to turn that program into a language the computer can understand.

 

A compiler is one such specialized computer program, used in the creation of other computer programs. A compiler takes the program you wrote in a language that people can read and changes it into a form the computer can understand and operate from (instructions made up of certain unique patterns of 1s and 0s). This final form is what we know as a program.

One important aspect of how a compiler works is that it takes all of the instructions in the program and turns them all into language that the computer can understand before actually executing the program. Meaning, it converts all the code into machine language and then runs it.

There is another similar specialized program called an interpreter. Interpreters convert the program instructions one at a time, only moving on to the next instruction when the computer has finished converting it and executing it.

COMPUTER ERGONOMICS: Ergonomics is a science concerned with designing and arranging things people use with the intention of assuring an efficient and safe interaction between people and things. It is a field of study that attempts to reduce strain, fatigue, and injuries by improving work space arrangement with the goal of attaining a comfortable, relaxed posture.

Working extended hours on computers without frequent breaks can have adverse impacts on your body. It can physically stress your body parts, e.g. if you are extending wrists, slouching, sitting without proper foot support or using poorly placed monitors. If you do not take proper care while working with computers, it may result in injuries with symptoms of pain, muscle fatigue, and reduced performance.

Laptops are not ergonomically designed for prolonged usage. It is advisable to use separate monitor and hand support so that your elbows can rest at a 90 degree angle. Also, it is wise to arrange your workstation so that your eyes are level with the monitor. While working with computers, sit straight with a chair that supports your back, use an ergonomically designed mouse if needed, and keep your feet parallel with the floor. It is recommended that you sit straight — aligning your ears, shoulders and hips — switch hands when using a mouse, and completely rest your wrists during breaks by taking your hands off the mouse.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

COMPUTER ERGONOMICS: It is good to take a brief break every 30-60 minutes to stretch, exercise, walk around, etc. You can Google good stretches and exercises to do daily. In the long run, it may help you avoid unnecessary pains.

Another important factor is that extended periods of sitting is not healthy. There are many potential solutions for this, including using a desk you can stand at or using a laptop stand. It’s a good idea to educate yourself in the dangers of sitting too much as well as the available solutions. This is all meant to increase your level of health — we hope this information helps!

KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS: A “shortcut” is a key or combination of keys you press on a keyboard to make something easier or faster. This is also called a “hot key”.

There are a few keys on your keyboard whose function you should understand.

One is called the “control” key (ctrl). The ctrl key is used in combination with another key to “control” your computer. Meaning, you use ctrl with other keys to make the computer perform commands. For example, in most word processors, “ctrl + s” will save the document you're typing.

There is also a “tab” key. “Tab” is short for “tabular” or “tabulator”. Tabular means having to do with or composed of tables or columns — something that is presented in a table format would be tabular. A tabulator is a thing (or a person) that arranges data in tables or columns. A tab can also be an indentation in a line of text usually equal to about five spaces. The tab key has various uses. It can be used to create a tab. The tab key can also be used in combination with other keys as a shortcut.

Another key is the “alternate” (alt) key. This key performs various functions when operating a computer, depending on the program or software you're using. For example, in most word processors, pressing “alt” will take you to the file menu. The alt key is also used in combination with other keys as a shortcut. For example: “alt + tab” allows you to alternate through different windows on your computer.

There are certain shortcuts we use all day, every day. They work whether you're doing stuff with photos, music, documents, or spreadsheets.

  1.  <Template-blank & Note>

ASSIGNMENT:

Utilize the following keyboard shortcuts:

Copy a selected item: Ctrl + C

Cut a selected item: Ctrl + X

Paste a selected item: Ctrl + V

Undo an action: Ctrl + Z

Redo that thing I just undid: Ctrl + Y

Select everything: Ctrl + A

Print: Ctrl + P

Save a file: Ctrl + S

Search an open file for a word or phrase: Ctrl + F

Switch between open windows: Alt + Tab

If you have lots of open windows and you're not sure exactly which one you need, press Alt + Tab, and get a quick thumbnail view of all open windows. Then, while holding down the Alt key, press the Tab key multiple times until you get to the window you want.

Clear away everything and show the desktop: Windows logo key + D

Use this shortcut when you want to minimize a lot of open windows at once to check something

on your desktop. “Clutter-to-clean” with two fingers.

Minimize the window: Windows logo key + Down Arrow

Minimizing a window is a surefire way to see what's underneath it. And it's fast to use the shortcut. If the window is maximized (covering the entire screen), it'll go to “normal” size. And if it's normal size, it'll minimize entirely.

Maximize the window: Windows logo key + Up Arrow. Maximizing windows follows the same concept as minimize.

Compare and contrast in a snap: Windows logo key + Left Arrow or Right Arrow.

Multitask with multiple monitors: Windows logo key + Shift + Right Arrow or Left Arrow

Do you use more than one monitor at a time? This shortcut allows you to shift an open window to your other monitor.

A popular shortcut is: Ctrl + Alt + Delete. This is used to open up Task Manager or to lock your computer.

But there are shortcuts for this shortcut. Open Task Manager: Ctrl + Shift + Esc. This simple shortcut whisks you straight to Task Manager — without any intermediary steps.

Lock your PC or switch users: Windows logo key + L. This shortcut locks your PC and instantly displays the login screen.

Choose a presentation display mode: Windows logo key + P

Zoom in/zoom out: Windows logo key + Plus Sign or Minus Sign

The Plus Sign key (+) zooms you in and the Minus Sign key (-) zooms you out. This lets you see small text on a web page or to check out the pixels in a photo.

Search for files and folders: Windows logo key + F

COMPUTER AND TECHNOLOGY BASICS COURSE EXAM

  1. What is a CPU?
  1.  “CPU” stands for “Control Program Unit.” The CPU is a computer's internal software, which directs other programs.
  2.  “CPU” stands for “Central Processing Unit.” The CPU is the brains of a computer and where the computations occur. CORRECT
  3.  “CPU” stands for “Control Pointing Unit.” The CPU is the director of a computer's activities.
  4. “CPU” stands for “Central Power Usage.” The CPU is the internal device monitoring a computer's voltage.

  1. What is a database?
  1.  A temporary storage location in a computing device, which allows a processor immediate access to recent data.
  2.  The central location in a computer where all application data is stored.
  3.  A basic set of data for populating a table.
  4.  An easily-accessible, structured collection of data stored in a computer. CORRECT

  1. What is a hard drive?
  1.  A high-capacity, self-contained storage device located inside or outside of a computer. CORRECT
  2.  Software designed to control a particular type of device attached to a computer.
  3.  A central location where all functions of the computer take place.
  4.  A system of computer components that cooperate to access stored data.

  1. What is “RAM”?
  1.  “RAM” stands for “Read Action Memory.” RAM is considered “read-only” memory.
  2.  “RAM” stands for “Remote Agent Memory.” RAM is often considered “helper” memory.
  3.  “RAM” stands for “Random Access Memory.” RAM is considered volatile or short-term memory. CORRECT
  4.  “RAM” stands for “Reduced Access Memory.” RAM acts as a security measure in reducing a user's access to specific areas of an Operating System.

  1. What is bandwidth?
  1.  The amount of information that can be sent or received over the Internet. CORRECT
  2.  The measurement of the width of the bands that connect the motherboard to the computer chassis.

  4.  The range of electronic frequency in a CPU clock.

  4.   “CSS” stands for “Calculation Summary Sheet.” CSS is used to keep a record of important information found on a web page.

  1.  Any dynamic website.

  2.  “DNS” stands for “Domain Number Suite.” DNS is responsible for tracking the number of nodes in a network.
  3.  “DNS” stands for “Dual Number System.” DNS allows a client and server to communicate through binary.
  4.  “DNS” stands for “Dual Network Server.” DNS refers to any server that transmits information through two networks.

  1.  A large computer known as a supercomputer.

  1.  Horizontal Transfer and Method Latency: a framework for testing speeds across networks.
  2.  Holographic Transfer Media Library: a library of programming languages for virtual and augmented reality.

  4.  Short for HoTMaiL: a popular webmail client in the mid-90's and early 2000's.

  1.  HyperText Transfer Protocol: the protocol used by the Internet to send and receive web page information. CORRECT
  2.  High-Temperature ThermoPlastic: the precursor to silicon, popular in hobby shop circuit boards.

  4.  Hollow-Text TyPe: a bubble font similar to comic sans, closely mirroring the handwriting of a child.

  1. What is “SPOOLing” (spooling)?
  1. “SPOOLing” stands for “Secure Processing Of Other Languages” Spooling is the secure process of shuttling instructions as an unbreakable group between computing languages.
  2.  “SPOOLing” stands for “Sub-Proxial Organized Orbital Link.” Spooling is the wireless scanning method used by WiFi routers.
  3. “SPOOLing” stands for “Self-Prioritizing Optical Organizational Language.” Spooling is the way optical circuits transfer information to other components in a central bus assembly.
  4.  “SPOOLing” stands for “Simultaneous Peripheral Operations On-Line.” Spooling is assigning tasks to a buffer, where a device can access them when ready. CORRECT

  1. What is a bus?
  1.  A collection of stored records in RAM. It was designed to provide a repository for sensitive data.
  2.  A distinct set of conductors carrying data and control signals within a computer system, to which pieces of equipment may be connected. CORRECT
  3.  An acronym for Bifurcated Universal System. It is the graphic-patterned symbol that allows an optical device to identify an individual component.

  1. United States Binary.

  1. In computers, what is a hub?
  1.  A place where programmers meet to collaborate on projects.

  3.  A machine that relays information to computers on a network. It will only send the information to the requesting computer.
  4.  A cover for a computer to protect it and give it style.

  1. What is LAN?
  1.  “LAN” stands for “Local Access Network.” A LAN is the internal communication bus in a midsize computer. It ensures all peripherals can communicate with the internal memory and output protocols.
  2.  “LAN” stands for “Los Angeles Networks.” LAN was formed by a small group of former Cisco Networks engineers. Their company was focused on outperforming their former employer, but unfortunately went out of business in September 1993.
  3.  “LAN” stands for “Light-Applied Networks.” Fiber-optic LAN connections are used for voice communications between intercontinental offices.
  4.  “LAN stands” for “Local Area Network.” A LAN is a small group of connected computers. A small business would use a LAN to provide all employees access to the company’s sales reports. CORRECT

  1. In computers, what is a client?
  1.  A customer of a software development firm.
  2.  A computer that retrieves information from or uses resources provided by a server or main computer. CORRECT
  3.  A term that describes a data packet that has been rejected by the CPU due to network latency.
  4.  A shortened term for “client-side asynchronous communications,” a standard upon which all computers bit-stripe GPU operation values.

  1. What is DSL?
  1.  “DSL” stands for “Discombobulated Syncopation Licensing,” and describes complex time mechanization routines by internal server buses.
  2.  “DSL” stands for “Digital Subscriber Line.” DSL uses telephone lines to connect a computer to the Internet with a relatively high bandwidth. CORRECT
  3.  “DSL” stands for “Disparate Sub-Link” and describes a Parent/Child relationship in a Software-As-A-Service (SAAS) network model.
  4.  “DSL” stands for “Distributed Synchronization Logic,” a special purpose dithering algorithm used in fuzzy logic, artificial intelligence subroutines.

  1. What is ethernet?
  1.  Ethernet is a gaseous connection used in place of wired connections between network nodes.
  2.  Ethernet refers to sub-space communications between radio telescopes.
  3.  “Ethernet” is the term used for a hypothetical network configuration and must be implemented before it can be installed in a client location.
  4.  Ethernet is a connection system used in broadband connections for high-speed Internet. CORRECT

  1. What is an IP address?
  1.  “IP” stands for “Inductive Prototype.” An IP address is the lab location for devices that have tested to be thermally incompatible with other network devices.
  2.  “IP” stands for ‘Internet Protocol.” An IP address is the network location generated for a device connected to the Internet. CORRECT
  3.  “IP” stands for “Intellectual Property.” An IP address is the physical location of company trade secrets.
  4.  “IP” stands for “Internally Predicated.” An IP address refers to an address self-designated by the network protocol generator.

  1. What is a modem?
  1. “Modem” stands for “Multiple Oscillations Deconstructions Every Minute.” A modem is a device that determines how many repetitions are needed per minute to break up the data before sending it to a receiving device.
  2. “Modem” stands for “Module Optic Data Electron Messaging.” A modem is a device that will modify carrier signals into a data stream and then change the stream back to its original form.
  3.  “Modem” stands for “Modulation/Demodulation.” A modem is a device that will modify a carrier signal to imprint some data and then change that signal back to its original state once finished with the data. CORRECT
  4. “Modem” stands for “Modularity Outgoing Definition Emitter Mask.” A modem is a device that uses a flux capacitor to break a signal into a stream of data and converts it on the back end to its original state.

  1. What is a router?
  1.  A physical device that enables an Internet connection to be shared with other devices. A router in a home would divide the Internet between phones, printers, and computers. CORRECT
  2.  A device that redirects the entire Internet bandwidth to one device to ensure maximum download and upload capacity for important tasks like video conferencing
  3.  A device that carves intricate patterns in metal computer components to send an electronic signal

  1. What is SSL?
  1. “SSL” stands for “Secure Systems License.” It is the standard security technology for establishing an encrypted link between a web server and a browser. This link ensures that all data passed between the web server and browsers remain public.
  2.  “SSL” stands for “Special Security License.” It is the standard security technology for establishing an encrypted link between a web server and a browser. This link ensures that all data passed between the web server and browsers remain private and integral.
  3.  “SSL” stands for “Secure Sockets Layer.” It is the standard security technology for establishing an encrypted link between a web server and a browser. This link ensures that all data passed between the web server and browsers remain public.
  4.  “SSL” stands for “Secure Sockets Layer.” It is the standard security technology for establishing an encrypted link between a web server and a browser. This link ensures that all data passed between the web server and browsers remain private and integral. CORRECT

  1. What is a cache?
  1.  A cache is a place to store something permanently in a computing environment. The purpose is to shorten data access times, remove latency, and alter input/output. It is typically used to change application performance.
  2.  A cache is a place to store something permanently in a computing environment. The purpose is to shorten data access times, reduce latency, and improve input/output. It is typically used to improve application performance.
  3.  A cache is a place to store something temporarily in a computing environment. The purpose is to lengthen data access times, increase latency, and slow down input/output. It is typically used to decrease application performance. CORRECT
  4.  A cache is a place to store something temporarily in a computing environment. The purpose is to shorten data access times, reduce latency, and improve input/output. It is typically used to improve application performance.

  1. What is the definition of Computer Science?

  1. In computers, what is the definition of buffer?
  1.  A buffer is an automated means of cleaning a CD/DVD-ROM Drive.

  3.  A buffer is a data area shared by hardware devices or program processes that operate at different speeds or with different sets of priorities. The buffer forces each device or process to operate once the other device or process has completed its operation.
  4.  A buffer is a region of physical memory storage used to temporarily store data while it is being moved from one place to another. CORRECT

  1. How is a worm virus different than a trojan virus?

  1. What is a “base two” number system?

  1. What is a “base five” number system?

  3.  A formula invented by Bill James to estimate the probability that team A will win a game, based on the true winning percentage of Team A and Team B.
  4.  A number system that uses five characters (0,1,2,3,4) to represent numbers. CORRECT

  1. What is the definition of “binary”?
  1.  Binary is the use of numbers containing only two digits (10, 11, 12, 13, etc).
  2.  Binary is a two-digit number system, which includes zero and two digits above zero.
  3.  Binary is an alphanumeric number system using one digit and one letter.

  1. What is a bit?
  1.  A bit is a website that is downloaded quickly. “Bit” stands for “Basic Internet Territory.”
  2.  A bit is a single piece of an image. “Bit” stands for “Bin Install Transfer.”
  3.  A bit is the smallest size of a single photo that can be downloaded at one time. “Bit”stands for “Bin Install Total.”
  4.  A bit is a unit of information expressed as either a 0 or 1 in binary notation. “Bit” is a blend of “binary” and “digit.” CORRECT

  1. What does “GB” stand for? What does it mean?
  1.  “GB” stands for “Gigabyte,” which is a billion bytes, or roughly 2^30 bytes. Gigabytes are used to measure storage capacity. CORRECT
  2.  “GB” stands for “Gamma Byte” which is a billion bytes, or 10^9 bytes. Gamma Bytes are used to measure transfer speed.
  3.  “GB” stands for “Gamma bit” which is a million bits, or 1024^3 bits. Gamma bits are used to measure transfer speed.
  4.  “GB” stands for “Gigabit” which means a million bits, or 10^9 bits. Gigabits are is used to measure storage capacity.

  1. Count to 5 using binary in rows.
  1.  00010, 00100, 01100, 01110, 11110
  2.  10,100,100,000,110,000,000,000
  3.  00101, 00100, 00011, 00010, 00001
  4.  00001, 00010, 00011, 00100, 00101 CORRECT

  1. Translate the following binary numbers into decimal numbers:

010 =_______

011001 =_______

011111 =_______

  1.  010 = 2, 011001 = 25, 011111 = 31 CORRECT
  2.  010 = 8, 011001 = 27, 011111 = 33
  3.  010 = 1, 011001 = 49, 011111 = 51
  4.  010 = 4 , 011001 = 13, 011111 = 29

  1. Answer the following binary addition problems:

001 + 010 = _____

0110 + 0010 = _____

  1.  001 + 010 = 1 + 2 = 3, 0110 + 0010 = 6 + 2 = 8 CORRECT
  2.  001 + 010 = 1 + 4 = 5, 0110 + 0010 = 12 + 4 = 16
  3.  001 + 010 = 1 + 2 = 3, 0110 + 0010 = 9 + 4 = 13
  4.  001 + 010 = 1 + 3 = 4, 0110 + 0010 = 12 + 4 = 16

  1. What is source code?
  1.  A machine language listing of commands to be compiled or assembled into an executable computer program. CORRECT
  2.  An ordinary text listing of commands to be compiled into the Matrix.
  3.  An ordinary text listing of commands to be compiled or assembled into an executable computer program.
  4.  A set of serialized data instructions from an image ready to be compiled or assembled.

  1. What is a byte?
  1.  A group of eight bytons operated on separately and considered a unit of time.
  2.  A group of eight bitcoins operated on as a unit and considered a unit of money.
  3.  A group of eight binary digits, or bits, operated on as a unit and considered a unit of memory size. CORRECT
  4.  A group of eight bytes operated on as a unit and considered a unit of font size.

  1. What is a BMP?
  1.  BMP is a file used to map bits to generate an image. “BMP” stands for “Bitmap” and is commonly used as a file type for images. CORRECT
  2.  BMP is a file used only to generate images when multiple colored images are involved. “BMP” stands for “Beautify Multiple Photographs.”
  3.  BMP is a file that is mostly used for mathematical calculation. “BMP” stands for “Binary Monetary Photographs.”
  4.  BMP is a file most commonly used for making text-related maps. “BMP” stands for “Building Maps Photography.”

  1. In computers, what does “initialize” mean?
  1.  Initialization is the process of locating and using the defined values for variable data that is used by a computer program. CORRECT
  2.  Initialization is the process of locating and using the defined values for constant data that is used by a computer program.
  3.  Initialization is the process of using the defined values for matrix data to close down the program when it locks up.
  4.  Initialization is the process the computer uses to boot up and get ready for use.

  1. In programming, what is a loop?
  1.  A collection of wires connected to the motherboard.
  2.  A set of code that repeats itself 2 times before moving on.
  3.  A set of code that will repeat until a certain criteria is met. CORRECT
  4.  “Loop” stands for “Lead Object Oriented Programming” and involves setting variable values before initializing an object.

  1. In regards to programming, what is syntax?
  1.  Syntax is the set of rules for formatting and combining characters in a programming language. CORRECT
  2.  Syntax is a way to edit the font of your code.
  3.  Syntax is the rules and guidelines that define how files are transferred over the Internet.
  4.  Syntax is the way to translate code into assembly language.

  1. What is a software developer?
  1.  A person who creates and modifies computer programs CORRECT
  2.  A person who develops the physical parts of a computer
  3.  A person that tests final products to maximize user experience
  4.  A person who has a masters degree or greater in computer science

  1. What is SEO?
  1.  “SEO” stands for “South End Order.” SEO is a loosely-organized group of computer programmers based in San Jose, California.
  2.  “SEO” stands for “Search Engine Optimizer.” Its purpose is to create a stable location among search results in a search engine where online viewers can always find your website.
  3.  “SEO” stands for “Search Engine Optimization.” SEO helps you to achieve a high ranking in search engine output. CORRECT
  4.  “SEO” stands for “Sent Error Operation.” SEO is the set of tasks assigned to a computer after reporting an error.

  1. What does “asynchronous” mean?
  1.  If something is asynchronous, it is happening at the same time.
  2.  If something is asynchronous, it follows a set pattern.
  3.  If something is asynchronous, it is happening at a different time than when other things happen. CORRECT
  4.  If something is asynchronous, it does not follow a set pattern.

  1. What does “bps” mean?
  1.  “bps” stands for “Billups Per Shift.” bps is a measure of data transfer velocity.
  2.  “bps” stands for “Bytes Per Second.” bps is a measure of a network's upload speed.
  3.  “bps” stands for “Bits Per Second.” bps is a measure of data transfer rate. CORRECT
  4.  “bps” stands “Batch Priority Scheduler.” bps is a program included in Windows 7 and up that integrates processes to speed performance.

  1. What does “Mbps” mean?
  1.  Stands for “Movement Bootcall Protocol System,” the measurement of response time between the mouse/keyboard and hard drive.
  2.  Stands for “Megabits Per Second,” the count of megabits transferred per second in a network. CORRECT
  3.  Stands for “Maximum Bits Per Second,” the maximum transfer speed capability of a router.
  4.  Stands for “Megabytes Per Second,” the data processing speed of a CPU.

  1. What does CRC mean?
  1.  “CRC” stands for “Computer Registry Corporation,” the curation company of computer registry numbers.
  2.  “CRC” stands for “Cyclic Redundancy Check.” It’s a method of code being added to data in order to check for errors during transmission, storage or retrieval. CORRECT
  3.  “CRC” stands for “Coordinating Random Computations,” the place in the computer that holds numbers computed for later use.
  4.  “CRC” stands for “Circling Reader Control,” the control function that helps words scroll down when they are read on a computer.

  1. What does a driver do in a computer?
  1.  A driver is a device that keeps internal computer devices working together.
  2.  A driver is the device that controls the movement of electricity inside a computer.
  3.  A driver is software needed for one physical device to recognize and talk to another physical device. CORRECT
  4.  A driver is another name for the person inputting information into a computer.

  1. What is an SD Card?
  1.  An SD card is a card that selects data previously set aside. “SD” stands for “Saved Data.”
  2.  An SD card is a card that initializes a newly installed program to begin. “SD” stands for “Start Delivery.”
  3.  An SD card is an internal card that adds memory directly to your hard drive. “SD” stands for “Super Datastorage.”
  4.  An SD card is a card that stores information (often used in cameras). “SD” stands for “Secure Digital.” CORRECT

  1. What is a high-level language?
  1.  A computer programming language that is closer to human languages and further from machine languages. CORRECT
  2.  An advanced programming language such as FORTRAN and Pascal that is closer to Assembly language than to human languages.
  3.  A language that only a computer can understand.
  4.  A more complex programming language, and therefore interpreted slower by a compiler.

  1. What is a low-level language?
  1.  A programming language used by beginning software developers.
  2.  A language that must be compiled first before it is understandable by a computer.
  3.  A low-level language is a programming language consisting mostly of numbers a computer can understand. CORRECT
  4.  A low-level language is a programming language that humans can understand

  1. What does a compiler do?
  1.  A compiler takes a set of code that a human wrote and changes it into instructions that a computer will understand. CORRECT
  2.  A compiler takes computer code and changes it into words humans can understand.
  3.  A compiler is the person who gives the software developer the directions for what the final product will be.
  4.  A compiler gathers all information for a coding project so is can be turned into code.

  1. What does an interpreter do?
  1.  An interpreter directly executes instructions written in a programming language without previously compiling them into a machine language program. CORRECT
  2.  An interpreter is used when a software developer does not have sufficient knowledge to understand what is written.
  3.  Interpreter software is used by new software developers for reference.
  4.  An interpreter takes individual lines of code and then converts them into instructions a computer will understand. Interpreters do this conversion at the end of the program.

  1. What does “assembly language” mean?
  1.  Assembly language is a high-level language used by the developers who prepare the code for execution.
  2.  Assembly language is a low-level computer code converted to machine language by an assembler. CORRECT
  3.  Assembly language is used by junior software developers to plan their coding before actual code is written.
  4.  Assembly language is the language used in programming language documentation.

  1. What is object-oriented programming?
  1.  A programming methodology where real world objects are mapped to a function. It is specifically used for testing.
  2.  A type of computer programming where programmers define data types and data structures, as well as the functions applied to them. CORRECT
  3.  A type of computer programming used in game development where objects on the screen are given properties corresponding closely to their real world counterpart.
  4.  A programming paradigm in which “for loops” are replaced with “while loops,” which limits bugs and enables code reuse.

  1. What does “scripting language” mean?
  1.  Scripting languages are used by people who don't know coding languages. It involves the use of pre-written “scripts” that will run when called.
  2.  A scripting language is a subset of high-level programming languages where the code is set and difficult to change.
  3.  This is a language used to make scripts, which are sets of code used to make a task automatic. CORRECT
  4.  A scripting language is a language that the software developer utilizes only for debugging.

  1. In computers, what is a gate?
  1.  It is a threshold of frequency that allows the CPU to function efficiently.
  2.  It simply stores and releases information depending on the user's settings.
  3.  It allows specific IP addresses to pass through a computer's Firewall.
  4.  It is a small electronic part that controls whether or not electricity flows to specific spots in the computer. CORRECT

  1. In computers, what does the clock do?
  1.  It allows software to be installed fluidly and virtually free of errors.
  2.  It tells the computer when to wake up after being put to sleep.
  3.  It controls every aspect of a computer system and ensures synchronization among all active nodes.
  4.  It is a special electronic device that can put out an exact amount of electricity, for an exact period of time, at very precise intervals. CORRECT

  1. What is “Gigahertz?”
  1.  A Gigahertz represents one entire cycle through a computer's processor.
  2.  It is a measurement of RAM RPM.
  3.  In computing, Gigahertz refers to the quality of each moving part.
  4.  Gigahertz measures the speed of a CPU. CORRECT

  1. What is the .NET framework?

  2.  A Microsoft application that allows users to enhance their programming skills.

  1. What is an OS?
  1.  “OS” stands for “Operating System,” the software that manages the other programs in a computer. CORRECT
  2.  “OS” stands for “Open System,” software made freely available for redistribution and modification.
  3.  “OS” stands for “Oscillating Stasis,” the process a computer goes through during boot-up. The result is a “warm” computer, ready for use.
  4.  “OS” stands for “Off-Site,” a computer system stored securely away from any activity for safety and security of data.

  1. Inside your computer, what is the heat sink and what does it do?
  1.  A USB-connected computer peripheral designed to eliminate excess heat caused by static electricity.
  2.  A common computer virus that causes overheating of the main processing units.
  3.  A passive heat exchanger that extracts heat from parts of your computer such as the processor. CORRECT
  4.  An open source software designed by Oracle in the late 1980's. It removes unnecessary slowdowns in your computer, which is the most common cause of overheating.

  1. What is a chip and what does it do?
  1.  A heavy-duty board used for wiring circuits. Short for “microwavable chip.”
  2.  A punched hole in a circuit board for storing data.
  3.  Short for microchip, a small piece of semiconductor material carrying many circuits. CORRECT
  4.  A form of memory-storage used in the early 90’s. Its wavy form resembled a potato chip.
